<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/78206240-rupert-wolfe-murray"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1519500104i/78206240._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/78206240-rupert-wolfe-murray">Rupert Wolfe-Murray</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Malcolm Gladwell says he starts planning his next book with the ending, and then everything else falls into place. The ending of A Handful of Dust is <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Malcolm Gladwell says he starts planning his next book with the ending, and then everything else falls into place. The ending of A Handful of Dust is brilliant because it's surprising, tragic, absurd and imaginative. I had a sense of impending doom as Tony heads deeper into a jungle with no obvious way out, but his eventual fate has a cruel irony to it.<br /><br />Another great feature of the ending is the cut to the future where Brenda has been transformed from humiliating poverty into wife of an MP; what I love about the way that Waugh does it is that he skips all the detail about how they got together. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
