        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2093241256" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7431817492084491879">Evelyn Waugh&apos;s writing is delightfully (and spitefully) mischievous. He&apos;s as witty as Oscar Wilde and as caustic as drain cleaner.<br/>Something of a pessimist and a social misfit, Waugh loved to send up the chattering classes of which he was a part. This book also has an autobiographical aspect to it and centres on his inside view of upper-class selfishness and the erosion of spiritual values in post-WWI England.</span>
  <span id="freeText7431817492084491879" style="display:none">Evelyn Waugh's writing is delightfully (and spitefully) mischievous. He's as witty as Oscar Wilde and as caustic as drain cleaner.<br />Something of a pessimist and a social misfit, Waugh loved to send up the chattering classes of which he was a part. This book also has an autobiographical aspect to it and centres on his inside view of upper-class selfishness and the erosion of spiritual values in post-WWI England.</span>
