    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1582237235" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1582237235" />
    <a title="John" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21938800-john"><img alt="John" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620927870p2/21938800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1582237235?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John" href="/user/show/21938800-john">John</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141183961" href="/book/show/827814.A_Handful_of_Dust">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21938800-john?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21938800-john?shelf=evelyn-waugh">evelyn-waugh</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1582237235" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5383100880343277334">If you like black humour this is an enjoyable book. There are some genuinely some laugh out loud scenes especially with Tony and Brenda&apos;s young son John. Coupled with insights to the decay of the upper classes and the weird rules they lived by. At times you want to shake Tony Last out of his placidity and it is a relief when he develops a backbone when his gothic home of Hetton is threatened by Brenda. I would also say that Brenda is a woman who gives villainy a bad name. <br/><br/>The switch to South Ame</span>
  <span id="freeText5383100880343277334" style="display:none">If you like black humour this is an enjoyable book. There are some genuinely some laugh out loud scenes especially with Tony and Brenda's young son John. Coupled with insights to the decay of the upper classes and the weird rules they lived by. At times you want to shake Tony Last out of his placidity and it is a relief when he develops a backbone when his gothic home of Hetton is threatened by Brenda. I would also say that Brenda is a woman who gives villainy a bad name. <br /><br />The switch to South American jungles and the insane Mr Todd and the reading of Dickens is both comedic and tragic. I enjoyed A Handful of Dust and can understand why it is considered one of Waugh's best novels. It was also interesting to read the alternative ending Waugh wrote.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5383100880343277334" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


