    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1679548276" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1679548276" />
    <a title="Gary" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45221326-gary"><img alt="Gary" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621058373p2/45221326.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1679548276?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gary" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gary" href="/user/show/45221326-gary">Gary</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140111507" href="/book/show/827817.A_Handful_Of_Dust">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Gary by: </span>
      Sas Tovee-Lynch
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45221326-gary?shelf=relationships-romance">relationships-romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45221326-gary?shelf=social-commentary">social-commentary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45221326-gary?shelf=adventure-derring-do">adventure-derring-do</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1679548276" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6362992299374053442">Overall I really enjoyed this book, though it changed so dramatically about half way through that I wasn’t sure at first if I liked it after that, because it was not what I was expecting.<br/><br/>The story is essentially one of upper class relationships and behaviour between the wars. The characters are filthy rich by most people’s standards but several of them never have enough money because they are maintaining enormous ancestral homes that cost a fortune to run. This is the cause of a lot of their pro</span>
  <span id="freeText6362992299374053442" style="display:none">Overall I really enjoyed this book, though it changed so dramatically about half way through that I wasn’t sure at first if I liked it after that, because it was not what I was expecting.<br /><br />The story is essentially one of upper class relationships and behaviour between the wars. The characters are filthy rich by most people’s standards but several of them never have enough money because they are maintaining enormous ancestral homes that cost a fortune to run. This is the cause of a lot of their problems: the ‘Lord of the Manor’ feels an ancient and heavy burden of responsibility towards his estate, tenants and most of the village, the populace of which still relies heavily on the estate for its economic wellbeing.<br /><br />This was a time in England when the value of agricultural land had declined and continued to do so and huge inherited estates became more of a burden than an asset. Many large country houses were being sold off to nouveau-riche Americans, who themselves were indulging themselves in their wealth – wealth born of a very different kind of business; a hard-nosed ‘life is tough, so fight for what you want’ sort of wealth, which many Americans then invested – squandered in some cases, no doubt – buying British country houses and turning them into hotels, schools and golf resorts. The people selling them these piles were often rent by conflicting emotions: enormous guilt and feelings of failure at having to sell up the family seat, sometimes centuries in the making: guilt towards their servants and tenants, whom they felt they had let down, guilt towards the older members of their families who did not understand that the world had changed and a system originally based on feudalism was no longer necessary or desirable. Mind you, they must have also felt huge relief once the money was in the bank.<br /><br />This is also a time when many rich people lived for their social lives (not having to trouble themselves with a job), when debutantes still ‘came out’ at balls (a system whereby young women were ‘introduced into society’, i.e. declared their availability for marriage), when lunching at the club or dining with ones friends was the highlight of their day. I guess that’s what some rich people always do, now and back then, though today it is all less formal.<br /><br />This was the late 1920s, a time when Victorian England and the Empire were still held in high esteem by many and, perhaps, mourned as the Empire crumbled and was given away (not before time) and the world had moved on enormously – the Great War had seen to that, but younger people demanded and got more freedom than their parents (as ever) and wanted more to life than duty and responsibility.<br /><br />It was also a time when the Victorian ‘system’ of marriage still operated; i.e. it was okay to have extra marital affairs if that meant you were kinder and remained loyal to your spouse ‘til death us do part’ and divorce was still frowned upon.<br /><br />Some spoilers…<br />A Handful of Dust is set in this atmosphere. It concerns a husband who feels the weight of his responsibilities as the ‘Lord of the Manor’, which he rather likes, and who loves his large but not very attractive or particularly historical house. His wife, on the other hand, hates living in the middle of nowhere in a not very attractive old house with not much to do, whilst her friends live and continually socialise in London. She is bored and a bit envious which, as we all know, often leads to trouble.<br /><br />She embarks on an affair with a young man who is quite good looking but pretty useless, having no money, no status and is a bit of a joke to Society. The story develops along these lines until the husband finds out and things come to a head – and then it all changes completely! I won’t reveal how but it seemed a huge leap in plot development.<br />Waugh was clever because truth is stranger than fiction generally and people do strange things when they experience a big and unwelcome change in their lives. Suffice to say that the main protagonists both get more than they expected and both look rather foolish.<br /><br />The book is very well written; Waugh is able to give sufficient characterisation in just a few words and the story certainly grips you. The ending is totally unpredictable until over half way through.<br /><br />I will read this one again and read some more Waugh.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6362992299374053442" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


