    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3100179094" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3100179094" />
    <a title="Fonch" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8647009-fonch"><img alt="Fonch" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1333994582p2/8647009.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3100179094?book_show_action=true">Dec 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fonch" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fonch" href="/user/show/8647009-fonch">Fonch</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3100179094" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2239390988179248759">Ladies and gentlemen. In this case I take up a book, which I read late last year. I told you, I was very interested in writing some criticism of my Christmas readings, because, although I think, I didn&apos;t put any five. There was some interesting book and&quot;A handful of dust&quot;. The first thing you&apos;ve missed them is why did you put a (3) on it? The first thing, which I mean is one thing, that this three is, very misleading, and does not always reflect the reality of the whole. When I put a three books</span>
  <span id="freeText2239390988179248759" style="display:none">Ladies and gentlemen. In this case I take up a book, which I read late last year. I told you, I was very interested in writing some criticism of my Christmas readings, because, although I think, I didn't put any five. There was some interesting book and"A handful of dust". The first thing you've missed them is why did you put a (3) on it? The first thing, which I mean is one thing, that this three is, very misleading, and does not always reflect the reality of the whole. When I put a three books that I have liked, but that have been saved from burning for little, but also very good books, which aspire to a lot and for small things have not managed to reach my Olympus.<br />The first thing I must say is that the note in this book is not (3), but a (3.5-3,75). This is not a (3), for example as"A Tourist in Africa"that passed for very little <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12213176-a-tourist-in-africa-evelyn-waugh">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1...</a> <br />, or as"Loved Ones" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7136270-los-seres-queridos">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7...</a>. Nor like"Scoop" this is not a novel, which he approved by the hairs, like the other two books quoted, but a novel, which reflects what is a three a good book, which I liked <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/30919.Scoop">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3...</a>. No"A handful of dust" really happens to us as in Victor Hugo's wonderful novel"Los misérables" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24280.Les_Mis_rables?ac=1&amp;from_search=true&amp;qid=XQjleziEMm&amp;rank=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2...</a> <br /> when the immortal writer of romanticism describes the Battle of Waterloo to us and tells us, that contrary to what we suppose or might suppose Napoleon was not in decline, but that we were in front of the best Napoleon, who was never better, and who only lost by god's will. Something similar can be said about Evelyn Waugh <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/11315.Evelyn_Waugh">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> <br />of this novel. Perhaps not the best Waugh, who, in spite of modern and secularist critics, who consider the best of Evelyn Waugh is his Pre-Brideshead period. I openly disagreed. I know Evelyn Waugh wouldn't be happy at all, that she thought her best novel was"Brideshead Revisited" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/30933.Brideshead_Revisited?ac=1&amp;from_search=true&amp;qid=dNvvGQhdRv&amp;rank=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3...</a> , , for me the best he wrote it from there. With all this book is one of the best Evelyn Waugh has written without hesitation, and a masterpiece, and it is much closer to the four, than to the two. I daresay this is one of the most moral and courageous novels written by the great English writer and the reason I didn't put the four stars on it was two. First because Waugh's great work was erected by the work of divine grace was coming and that was "Brideshead Revisited". Here providence is, and is glimpsed, but it is not quite 100%, as if it will be in later works of the great English Catholic writer (for me one of my favorite writers). Perhaps when you list your favorite Catholic writers, don't think of Waugh (even though he may have quite possibly written the best Catholic novel of the last century, with the exception of the "Lord of the Rings" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33.The_Lord_of_the_Rings?ac=1&amp;from_search=true&amp;qid=bpX8s1LVgo&amp;rank=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3...</a> though I don't think, that the Waugh agree with me). All in all, I appreciate and love them, and I've been following Waugh's descendants with enormous. More out of devotion to the English writer than for anything else, because what interests me about them no longer has it, but I'm a faithful dog. This book is enormously moral, and despite it was written in the 1930s. It has been a prophetic book in every way. It is more than just a brilliant satire, such as "Decline and Fall" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/30929.Decline_and_Fall?ac=1&amp;from_search=true&amp;qid=R47EHNDxBY&amp;rank=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3...</a> or "Black mischief". This is one of the novels most hostile to divorce, ever written, and which shows the harm divorce causes in society. That's why we say, it's a very moral novel, because Evelyn Waugh doesn't put any kind of balm in and shows the destruction of marriage, like what is a catastrophe to society, and the tragedy that the protagonists suffer because of it. I put the Spanish case, because it is the one that touches me most present, but all those people who promoted the legalization of divorce, as then would promote that of abortion, and of people of the same sex, and now euthanasia. That society, perhaps, must have been very mindful of this book. The first Evelyn Waugh knows what he is talking about, because he lived it in his own flesh, when he divorced Evelyn, though I believe, that while he did not find the bliss because of the changes that occurred by the Second Vatican Council. I believe that his second wife the adorable Laura Herbert did something similar to what Domenica Plessington did for Guy Crouchback in the "Sword of Honour" trilogy <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/30932.The_Sword_of_Honour_Trilogy">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3...</a> and it's getting things right for him. As far as possible it was a source of tranquility, for Evelyn, he endured the variableness of his temper, expoleoed his literary talent, was his greatest critic, and gave him the pleasures of marital life. That's why Waugh knows what he's talking about when he writes this magnificent novel that I didn't put four stars to for a reason, and it's because those characters. A friend of Evelyn Waugh perhaps that controversial friendship, which embodies the modern world, that Evelyn Waugh criticized, through Hooper. Cyril Conolly <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/51067.Cyril_Connolly">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> he said that at first "A handful of dust" is the story of a happy family, and I add that it is destroyed by the superstition of divorce. What slain me about this novel is that the corrective inflicted by Waugh on his characters, though logical, and realistic was in my opinion a little drastic. The novel being extraordinary is magnificent, but also very cruel to the characters. Maybe they're cartoons, or screds, as brilliantly defined by Valle Inclán in his play "Lights of Bohemia" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/65213.Luces_de_bohemia?ac=1&amp;from_search=true&amp;qid=JbfgfIeN7M&amp;rank=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6...</a> (perhaps the definition of sperm is of the unsalvageable in the overrated play of the Galician writer). They may be cartoons, and ridiculous characters, and I know Waugh will be mad from the grave with a server. But even though they're stupid, ridiculous, I came to love them except maybe the adulterous John Beaver, but the rest I came to love them with affection, and for that I was sorry for their luck. Because one of the things Evelyn Waugh shows us in this masterful novel is that there are fates worse than death, and this is the fate that inflicts on his characters. The author was realistic, and despite its comic background the work has a bitter character, but I, who am the enemy of divorce, saw me taking pity on those wretched creatures both Anthony Last and Brenda Last. Perhaps of all Evelyn Waugh's novels, they may have the bitterest fate. I know, I'm beating them up with this fictional character theme, but to me they're not fantasy creatures, but characters when they're created have a life of their own. My friends Jorge Sáez Criado, and Manuel Alfonseca <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14769537.Jorge_S_ez_Criado">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/1117598.Manuel_Alfonseca">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> have often been surprised to see what their fictional creatures were doing. In fact, my friend was surprised at what a character of his like Vicky Ramos was doing, one of his transition detectives. The character came to life, and did something the author hadn't thought of (it didn't come to such a dramatic situation as Kim Basinger's Cool film Gabriel Byrne, and Brad Pitt, nor an Unamunian ending as in stranger than fiction, or in Inkheart <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28194.Inkheart?ac=1&amp;from_search=true&amp;qid=CacVYjneMz&amp;rank=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2...</a> <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/25536.Miguel_de_Unamuno">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> (That's why I don't like Writers like George R.R. Martin, who to please the bloodlust of their readers is dedicated to creating characters, and giving them the most disgusting deaths, that come to mind, because it is a way of wasting talent, and prevents them from developing. Death, or it must be a punishment or the culmination of a character who has reached his goal <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/series/43790-a-song-of-ice-and-fire">https://www.goodreads.com/series/4379...</a> <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/346732.George_R_R_Martin">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> ). <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/series/183665-los-sabuesos-de-la-transici-n">https://www.goodreads.com/series/1836...</a> This subject my friend already treated my best friend in his very interesting "Jacob's ladder" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24279520-jacob-s-ladder?ac=1&amp;from_search=true&amp;qid=PMgi7Hkknc&amp;rank=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2...</a> The writer must think of one thing, that he is a sub-creator, and that in turn he is a character of an even more wonderful novel, which ends up culminating in an end that of salvation. That is the destiny of every human being created by God. See if it's saved or not. That is his mystical quest and the ultimate end of all. That's the only one, but, or flaw I put to a masterful novel, that has it all. The so-called reference to myths in this case Waugh is based on the Arturic mythology and the relationship between Geneva and Lancelot to tell the adulterinous romance between Beaver (I've never seen the most evil beaver except that of Mel Gibson's film). We see that drinking from the classics was very common at the time, and Waugh does so with incredible, as he did in the "Sword of Honor" trilogy cited above, when he compares him to Menelaus, and his adulterous wife Virginia Troy to Helen of Troy. It's funny, but it's the opposite of what you do now. Fiction was previously adapted to classical canons, and now the myth is reinterpreted in a postmodern and postmodern, and relativistic way, to please exclusive lobbyists. It is a delight, and a great joy to see the almost-nobiliar atmosphere (something I always wish Waugh, who was a bourgeois of aristocratic tendencies, and in fact made us love the British nobility by overcoming the previous models of Maurice Baring's novels <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/13240.Maurice_Baring">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> and Robert Robert Benson <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/330845.Robert_Hugh_Benson">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> ) and bucolic in which both Anthony and Brenda move. For example, the parish priest's sermons are hilarious, he always says an ancient sermon, and he does not change it, even if it is from the time of Queen Victoria. In fact, the part of the tragedy is Brenda's tedium, routine, and monotony. That they have more to do with tragedy than the pathetic love attempts of John Beaver and his mother. Also Brenda a woman already made has something of Cougar, or MILF. Brenda's son and Anthony Last, though funny to me, i found him charming, especially the hilarious scenes he has with a suitor that Brenda is going to find her husband, to forget about her, and consent to allow her adultery or give him a divorce. I'll always have a doubt like Jenny Abdul Akbar's on-go-by-hued muley. Precisely this little character, who will star in his moment "A gone with the wind" (I can not reveal why, but if you have seen the film, or read the novel you will understand it). Anyway, there's almost deterministic Wugh. However, it is from the disappearance of this character, that while Christopher Nolan's wonderful film Interestellar explains that Murphy's law is not that something bad is going to happen, but that in the wake of a fact a chain of facts will occur. Interestingly it is from this moment on, when a succession of facts ends up destroying the Last, and in some cases giving them a fate worse than death. The characters' friends don't help either. . Although Anthony Last is a friend of his wife's former suitor. This relationship reminds me of the one Guy Crouchback is going to have with another ex of his wife. In this novel we will see one of the scenarios that will be important in "Brideshead revisited" the Old Hundreth, as Anthony and his friend will leave brown peaks just like Lord Sebastian Flyte and Charles Ryder. In fact, after the catastrophe, we'll see attempts by Anthony to fix his life, but with every decision he makes, he'll make it worse. Her relationship with a single mother she decides to date is curious. Social clubs are very well described, and the cold social system that will be Brenda's undoing, and that hasn't changed much either. . Because in the end divorce is almost never friendly (in fact, it's a failure of two people), it generates crunch, and it's an economic decline, for the one who gets it, and that's superbly described by Evelyn Waugh. Charles's case with his ex-wife Celia is very rare. One wonders if before taking such a disastrous step, but it is better worth attending a COF, or as Reverend Playfield says in "The Quiet Man." "Not worth fighting for your partner's love" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/407432.The_Quiet_Man_and_Other_Stories?ac=1&amp;from_search=true&amp;qid=noIkpiTqiV&amp;rank=3">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4...</a> Also although in a parodic way Waugh offers us a great adventure, which will end up being terrible, and I will not give him the adjective that he intended to give him, because the shrewd user would discover what fate has in store for Tony Last. But it's a terrible outcome. A living death. So terrifying, he has appeared in several horror anthologies. As for Brenda, she also gets a punishment. Her fate is very dark and it was a fate from which Virginia escaped by the hair. In fact many Wavian scholars have wanted to see in an allusion to a certain Brenda a reference to this character. To sum up a great novel, which will make you think and reflect, apart from laughing, but I warn you, if you are too sensitive do not read it, even if you did you would miss a masterpiece of literature of the last century. <br /></span>
