    <a title="Greg" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39346323-greg"><img alt="Greg" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513962691p2/39346323.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1775722946?book_show_action=true">Oct 04, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greg" href="/user/show/39346323-greg">Greg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39346323-greg?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1775722946" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8760107243669338419">England is between two World Wars, and when tragedy strikes a family in the form of a death, no one seems very upset. Are the English simply numb from the loss of almost an entire generation of men due to WW1? Or are the upper class simply ripe for satire? I think it&apos;s a little of both until towards the end of the book a woman wants a divorce so her husband basically hires a woman to spend a weekend with him so that he can be blamed for infidelity while the wife is the one who had been having an</span>
  <span id="freeText8760107243669338419" style="display:none">England is between two World Wars, and when tragedy strikes a family in the form of a death, no one seems very upset. Are the English simply numb from the loss of almost an entire generation of men due to WW1? Or are the upper class simply ripe for satire? I think it's a little of both until towards the end of the book a woman wants a divorce so her husband basically hires a woman to spend a weekend with him so that he can be blamed for infidelity while the wife is the one who had been having an affair. This is satire, surely this isn't a custom of any class of people. But then the story takes a turn for the weird, as the husband disappears and... well that would be too much of a spoiler to reveal here. There is no one to like here except Mrs. Rattery, who plays 4-pack solitaire as her way of dealing with the chaos of the death, the chaos of everything. She's outside it all, sometimes literally above it all (she flies her own plane) and goes her own way. And nobody in the book likes her. But they like each other: everyone but Mrs. Rattery can smell a rat a mile away. A book jacket blurb tells us that this is "Waugh at his most scathing," but I'm not clear on this point: the English are indeed, at this point of time, numb. I'm not sure if the English are ripe for a "scathing." This is an odd work, a bit uneven in tone, but compulsively readable. It's a page-turner in every sense of the term. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8760107243669338419" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


